frameDefinitions: In this frame an Action is evaluated with respect to how fairly, justly or equitably the Action affects the Affected_party.
The Support, a phenomenon or fact,  lends support to a claim or proposed course of action, the Proposition, where the Domain_of_relevance may also be expressed.

Using Evidence, which may or may not be expressed, a Cognizer recognizes or proves that Concept1 is associated causally or collocationally with another concept, Concept2.
In this frame either a Stimulus brings about a particular emotion or experience in the Experiencer or  saliently fails to bring about a particular experience.
frameExamples: Smithers was being very <t>fair</t> about the distribution of supplies.
The latest poll results <t>show</t> that support of the president is at an all-time low.

listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Actor</fen> is the individual who performs the <fen>Action</fen> and can thus be characterized with repsect to how that <fen>Action</fen> affects the <fen>Affected_party</fen>.
The <fen>Action</fen> is judged based on how just and appopriate it is to the <fen>Affected_party</fen> in a particular situation.
The <fen>Grounds</fen> is the event or state that requires some decision or action in response to it for which the <fen>Actor</fen> is judged.
The <fen>Affected_party</fen>'s treatment is what determines the evaluation of the <fen>Actor</fen>'s <fen>Action</fen>.
Support is a fact that lends epistemic support to a claim, or that provides a reason for a course of action. Typically it is expressed as an External Argument.
This is a belief, claim, or proposed course of action to which the Support lends validity. Normally it is expressed as a Finite Clause Complement:
The <fen>Evaluee</fen> is being judged for its quality.
This role marks expressions that denote a scalar property of the <fen>Evaluee</fen> with respect to which the <fen>Evaluee</fen> is judged.
The <fen>Evaluee</fen> is the person whose <fen>Behavior</fen> towards other human beings is being evaluated.
The <fen>Affected_party</fen> is the entity which is positively or negatively treated by the <fen>Evaluee</fen>.
The <fen>Behavior</fen> is the action of the <fen>Evaluee</fen> on which the evaluation of the <fen>Evaluee</fen>'s character is based.
The <fen>Topic</fen> is the situation or person that the <fen>Evaluee</fen>'s <fen>Behavior</fen> responds to or is related to.
The <fen>Expressor</fen> is the body part or action by a body part which indicates the character of the <fen>Evaluee</fen>.
The individual whose point of view is taken in assigning the evaluation denoted by the target.
<fen>Concept1</fen> is the phenomenon which is believed to be related to <fen>Concept2</fen>.
The phenomenon which is believed to be linked to Concept1.
The sentient entity that recognizes the causal connection.
The phenomena which are believed to be related.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Cognizer</fen> make the connection.
The location where the Cognizer makes the connection.
The <fen>Stimulus</fen> is the object or event which brings about the emotion in the <fen>Experiencer</fen>.
listRoleExamples: <fex>The fact that you lied to me</fex> shows that I shouldn't trust you.
The fact that you lied to me shows <fex>that I shouldn't trust you</fex>.
The Beaujolais Nouveau is dazzling <fex>in freshness</fex>.
<fex>In my book</fex>, that wasn't very gracious.
